otocol and reproducibility info\n  (random seeds, number of runs, hardware, execution time)\n\n## 4. Results\n- Key findings with supporting data and figures\n- Tables comparing methods, conditions, or systems\n- Visualizations with clear labels, units, and legends\n- Output file locations (results/, figures/, etc.)\n\n## 5. Analysis &amp; Discussion\n- Interpretation in context of hypothesis\n- Comparison to baselines, prior work, or literature values\n- Statistical significance and effect sizes where applicable\n- Error analysis and failure modes\n- Surprises and unexpected insights\n\n## 6. Limitations\n- Methodological limitations\n- Data or scope constraints\n- Assumptions and threats to validity\n- What could invalidate these results\n\n## 7. Conclusions &amp; Next Steps\n- Clear answer to research question (2-3 sentences)\n- Practical and theoretical implications\n- Recommended follow-up experiments or analyses\n- Open questions raised by this research\n\nNOTE: Your research domain may define a more specific report structure.\nCheck domain-specific guidelines for detailed reporting requirements tailored\nto your field (e.g., battery electrochemistry, machine learning, mathematics).\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n\nDELIVERABLE 2: Well-commented code and optional CODE_WALKTHROUGH.md\n\nEnsure code is self-documenting with clear comments and docstrings.\nOptionally create CODE_WALKTHROUGH.md with:\n\n## Code Structure Overview\n- Organization of notebook sections\n- What each major section does\n- Data flow diagram (if complex)\n\n## Environment Setup\n```python\n# Required libraries\nimport ...\n\n# Configuration\nconfig = {...}\n```\n\n## Key Functions and Classes\n\nFor each important function/class:\n\n### `function_name(args)`\n**Purpose**: What it does\n\n**Arguments**:\n- `arg1`: Description and type\n- `arg2`: Description and type\n\n**Returns**: What it returns\n\n**Design Rationale**: Why implemented this way\n